## Required Functionality
### Form Validation
- Include basic HTML5 validation attributes (`required`, `type`, `pattern`)
- Add client-side JavaScript validation for better UX
- Display validation error messages
- Handle form submission properly
- ALWAYS wrap all form inputs in a `<form>` element with proper `method` and `action` attributes
- Ensure placeholder text matches the actual field purpose (don't use "Enter Your Car Name" for a person's name field)

### Interactive Elements
- All buttons must be functional with proper event handlers
- Form inputs must be controllable (React controlled components)
- Include loading states for async operations
- Add hover and focus states for interactive elements
- Use actual `<input type="checkbox">` elements, not styled divs for checkboxes
- Implement proper checkbox state management with form data

### Input Field Requirements
- Use correct input types: `email` for emails, `tel` for phone numbers, `password` for passwords
- Ensure proper label-input associations with `for` and `id` attributes
- Add appropriate `name` attributes for form submission
- Include proper `autocomplete` attributes for better UX
- Use semantic placeholders that match field purpose

### Country/Phone Number Fields
- Implement functional country code selection, not just static display
- Use proper dropdown/select elements for country selection
- Handle phone number formatting and validation
- Include proper flag icons or country selection UI

### Focus and Interaction States
- Add proper CSS focus states for all interactive elements
- Implement hover effects for buttons and clickable elements  
- Use CSS transitions for smooth state changes
- Avoid JavaScript-only styling - use CSS for visual states

### State Management
- Use React state for form data management
- Include error state management
- Add loading states for form submission
- Handle success/failure states

## Performance Considerations
### Optimization
- Use CSS custom properties for consistent theming
- Minimize CSS specificity conflicts
- Use efficient selectors
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders in React components
- Implement proper memoization where needed

### Bundle Size
- Avoid importing entire utility libraries when only using a few classes
- Use tree-shaking friendly imports
- Minimize inline styles and complex class combinations

## Testing Considerations
### Testability
- Add proper `data-testid` attributes for testing
- Use semantic HTML that works well with testing libraries
- Include proper ARIA labels for accessibility testing
- Structure components to be easily unit testable

## File Organization
### Structure
- Separate styles into dedicated CSS/SCSS files when not using CSS-in-JS
- Group related components in logical folders
- Use consistent naming conventions across files
- Include TypeScript interfaces in separate files when complex

## Integration Guidelines
### API Integration
- Design forms to work with real backend APIs
- Include proper error handling for network requests
- Add loading states during API calls
- Handle different response scenarios (success, error, validation errors)

### State Management
- Design components to work with global state management (Redux, Context, etc.)
- Make components reusable and configurable
- Separate business logic from presentation logic

## Quality Checklist
Before considering Figma MCP output complete, ensure:
- ✅ All interactive elements are functional
- ✅ Forms use proper HTML form elements with `<form>` wrapper
- ✅ Accessibility attributes are present (`for`, `id`, `aria-*`, `role`)
- ✅ Responsive design is implemented (no fixed pixel positioning)
- ✅ No excessive div nesting (max 3 levels)
- ✅ Semantic HTML is used throughout (`button`, `input`, `label`, etc.)
- ✅ CSS uses modern layout techniques (Grid/Flexbox, not absolute positioning)
- ✅ Form validation is implemented with proper error handling
- ✅ Error handling is included with `aria-live` regions
- ✅ Loading states are considered for async operations
- ✅ Component is reusable and configurable
- ✅ TypeScript types are properly defined (for React)
- ✅ Event handlers are implemented with proper state management
- ✅ Performance optimizations are applied
- ✅ Placeholder text matches field purpose
- ✅ Proper input types are used (`email`, `tel`, `password`)
- ✅ Label-input associations are correct (`for`/`id` matching)
- ✅ Checkboxes are actual input elements, not styled divs
- ✅ Country/phone selection is functional, not just decorative
- ✅ CSS borders are used instead of absolute positioned decorative elements
- ✅ Focus and hover states work properly
- ✅ Form can actually be submitted and handles validation errors
- ✅ Layout adapts to different screen sizes without breaking

## React Component Guidelines
- When using react, always look for the components in the project and use them instead of creating new ones or using basic html elements.
- Always look for shadcn components in the @/components folder.
- Analyze the components styling and the tailwind theme used to build the components.
- Use theme colors set in the root css file instead of hardcoded colors.